              <div class="quotetitle">Zac B wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I want to do a Belgian style American style Imperial IPA (something like an imperial Ommegang BPA). I wanted to do all-grain, but I realized that with 17-18 lb grain, I wouldn't have much water left for the sparge. I started from a DFH 90m clone recipe I found, did some hop substitutions based on what was available at northern brewer, and switched to Belgian malts.<br /><br />What I came up with was:<br /><br />9 lb belgian pale malt<br />1 lb belgian caramunich malt<br />6 lb pale liquid malt extract<br /><br />3 oz summit hops, 1 oz simcoe hops, 1 oz warrior hops 90 minute continuous hopping<br /><br />White Labs WLP500<br /><br />2 oz summit and 2 oz northern brewer hops for dry hopping.<br /><br />I'm placing the order later today. Has anybody tried anything similar?</div><br /><br />I placed this order with Northern Brewer yesterday evening. I'm hoping everything comes in by Saturday so I can brew late Saturday or Sunday. I've always racked off into a secondary before dry-hopping, but does it cause problems if I wait until fermentation finishes and dry hop right into the primary? I don't intend to reuse the yeast.

              

              
              
            </div>
