        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle">dak wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Is there a good rule on where the line between aging a beer and having it go stale lies? I know hoppy beers should be enjoyed young, and high gravity beers should age many months, but what about just normal ales? I have a Bock (with steam ale yeast) that's been in bottles almost two months and still tastes green.  I feel like it should have matured more by now.  <br /><br />Brewed at the end of December, bottled at the end of January, 1.054 down to 1.021, tastes slightly sour and I can't tell if I'm imagining the green apple flavor or not.</div><br />Anything that's not Hop Forward has considerably more potential to age well. Hop aromas are very liable to decline with any significant age.<br /><br />Hop Bitterness fairs better. Malt and esthers age best, given that infection and oxygen factors are limited. Bock will age better cold, and should be decent for 6 months or so, sometimes more. I've had very green brown ales age out and get quite excellent after 6months, but that was cold aged and kegged, where drop out tends to be almost inevitably complete by the last gallon or two, making the curve parabolic for quality.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
