          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle">dak wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Is there a good rule on where the line between aging a beer and having it go stale lies? I know hoppy beers should be enjoyed young, and high gravity beers should age many months, but what about just normal ales? I have a Bock (with steam ale yeast) that's been in bottles almost two months and still tastes green.  I feel like it should have matured more by now.  <br /></div><br /><br />General rule of thumb I've heard if 8+ ABV will generally age well. Exceptions are beers with wild yeasts and some hoppy beers. Mellower hop flavors might be fine on a barleywine, but probably not what you want with an imperial IPA. Process matters too. If you're working with a CO2 tank and can clear [nearly] all the oxygen from the bottle/keg headspace, then there's less danger of oxidation and stale flavors.<br /><br />1.021 seems rather high for a FG - especially with the low-ish OG. Maybe you had a stuck/incomplete fermentation.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
