          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle">Zac B wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Pocky Is God wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Zac B wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Zac B wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I want to do a Belgian style American style Imperial IPA (something like an imperial Ommegang BPA). I wanted to do all-grain, but I realized that with 17-18 lb grain, I wouldn't have much water left for the sparge. I started from a DFH 90m clone recipe I found, did some hop substitutions based on what was available at northern brewer, and switched to Belgian malts.<br /><br />What I came up with was:<br /><br />9 lb belgian pale malt<br />1 lb belgian caramunich malt<br />6 lb pale liquid malt extract<br /><br />3 oz summit hops, 1 oz simcoe hops, 1 oz warrior hops 90 minute continuous hopping<br /><br />White Labs WLP500<br /><br />2 oz summit and 2 oz northern brewer hops for dry hopping.<br /><br />I'm placing the order later today. Has anybody tried anything similar?</div><br /><br />I placed this order with Northern Brewer yesterday evening. I'm hoping everything comes in by Saturday so I can brew late Saturday or Sunday. I've always racked off into a secondary before dry-hopping, but does it cause problems if I wait until fermentation finishes and dry hop right into the primary? I don't intend to reuse the yeast.</div><br /><br /><br />Racking to secondary will do wonders to clear up your beer. I would do it just for that. Do you plan on adding any whirlfloc or irish moss to your boil?</div><br /><br />I haven't in the past. I'm using a 6 gallon primary, and have a spare 5 gallon carboy that makes a good secondary. I might pick some up for this beer.</div><br /><br />I used a whirlfloc tablet. The wort looked like a bit like miso soup, and stuff is settling out nicely. I split the hops up into 30 little cups and added a cup every three minutes for the 90 minute boil. My OG was 1.095 vs 1.091 expected (70% mash efficiency). I did brew in a bag with a batch sparge.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
